<HEADLINE>
Species diversity through time
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> John Harshman &lt;jharshman.diespam...@pacbell.net&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-11-05T20:03:00 </POSTDATE>
For those interested, this monograph came bundled with the latest issue
of Paleobiology:

Stanley, S. M. 2007. An analysis of the history of marine animal
diversity. Paleobiology 33(4s):1-55.

In it, Steven M. Stanley does a series of analyses based on Sepkoski's
compendium of marine invertebrate genera. He comes to a number of
conclusions that may interest some of the TO regulars. (These are not
necessarily the bits that Stanley considers most important.)

1. Background rates of speciation and extinction are strongly
correlated; that is, groups with high speciation rates also have high
extinction rates.

2. Rates of extinction during mass extinctions are strongly correlated
with background extinction rates.

3. Sepkoski posited 3 faunas, termed the Cambrian, Paleozoic, and
Modern, based on their times of greatest diversity. The Cambrian fauna
never amounted to all that much, and Stanley ignores it; I will too. The
Paleozoic fauna suffered most severely from the end-Permian extinction
and never recovered its dominance. The Modern fauna, as the name
suggests, dominates modern oceans. Stanley suggests that the difference
lies in speciation/extinction rates, high for the Paleozoic fauna and
low for the Modern fauna.

4. During mass extinctions, taxa with high speciation/extinction rates
are preferentially eliminated (corollary of 1 and 2). Thus their risk of
total extinction is higher than for low speciation/extinction rate taxa.
Also, if there's variation in rate within a taxon, it will end up with a
lower average rate after the mass extinction.

5. Faunas have diversified at a constant exponential rate since the end
of the Cambrian, except for disturbances during mass extinctions. The
Paleozoic fauna, after the end-Permian, had its high-rate taxa mostly
eliminated, and has become more or less similar in rates to the Modern
fauna.

6. The apparent post-Paleozoic increase in the Modern fauna is real and
has continued at that contstant rate until the present. The pull of the
Recent can't account for it.

7. Species will continue to increase in number at an exponential rate in
the future, again excepting periods of mass extinction.

8. Sepkoski fit a logistic curve to history, i.e. with speciation
slowing down as some maximum capacity was approached. Stanley thinks the
exponential model fits history much better. And indeed it looks that way
from the figures he provides.

9. If you want to call this a trend of increasing complexity, well, it's
at least a trend of increasing numbers. Does quantity have a quality all
its own?

A caveat or two: I'm not entirely sure that all his methods are correct.
Conclusions apply directly only to taxa of well-skeletonized marine
invertebrates, i.e. the taxa that make up the bulk of the fossil record.
It's your choice whether you want to apply these lessons to
vertebrates, soft-bodied invertebrates, land animals, or plants. Offer
void where prohibited.
</POST>
