No. But when you concentrate on those groups with good fossil records,
you can get a considerably better estimate *for those groups*. Whether
you want to think that generalizes to all life is up to you. You also
have to suppose here that genera are good proxies for species. And this
paper also works if lots of species are missing from the record, as long
as what we have is an unbiased sample. The less taxonomic disparity you
cover, the more likely that is.
