It seems quite logical that high rates of speciation should be be strongly
correlated with high rates of extinction, there might even be an
autocorrelation effect depending on the sources of data (I would suspect
there might be).  The first logical model that comes to mind is of course
that high rates of speciation suggest a more variable environment and
therefore more variable relationships between phyla and the environment,
e.g., more variation in niches prompts more speciation.  If that is the case
the rates of extinction should also correlate with niche variation because
enhanced opportunities for error (niche variation) also enhances the chances
for mass die-offs.  Of course this says nothing about the kind of niche
variation... it could be environmental in the sense of temperature,
salinity, pH and so forth or it could be predators or diseases.  Any
population bottleneck in a variable environment can predispose a species for
a disastrous collapse.  In an evolutionary sense every species is shooting
for an unknown survival target within its niche as it were and with a very
variable environment the target is moving so evolutionary misses are more
probable.
