I am not really satisfied with any of these as an explanation
for the general extinction of rapidly speciating groups.
Breaking them out my preliminary objections are as follows:

(1)
high rates of dispersal                     high speciation rate
low  rates of dispersal                     low rate

(2)
patchy distributions and small populations  high speciation rate
vs. continuous, large populations           low rate

(3)
broad habitat preference                    high speciation rate
narrow habitat preference                   low rate

(4)
sterotypic behavior                         high speciation rate
flexible behavior                           low rate

(1) high dispersal rates are beneficial because, among other
things, it allows rapid expansion into newly available
niches and would be particularly beneficial during most
imaginable extinction events, since it would allow the
species to find the few survivable habits.

(2) If diversity is increasing exponentially aren't small
dispersed populations what we must have now?  If so this
cannot be the key element leading to generalized
extinctions.

(3) Narrow habitat preferences sounds like &quot;specialists&quot;.
It seems to me that generalists are at least as likely to
survive an extinction event as specialists are.

(4) Insects (including beetles!!) have stereotypic behavior so
that cannot be the key factor that lead to generalized
extinction.

Throwing a couple new darts at this problem, I would like to
suggest two alternative explanations that could link &quot;High
speciation rates&quot; with the long-term general extinction of
groups with that characteristic:

A) Could it just be a more stable genome vs a less stable one?
Animals with less stable genomes would tend to speciate more
but a mutation rate that was too high could be devastating when
the population became tiny under stress.

B) Could it be that the species that survive today are able to
incorporate more diversity within a single genome?  That is
they can reproduce with partners that are more genetically
dissimilar.  The ability to tolerate/incorporate more genetic
diversity within a species would decrease speciation because
the members could live in a territory that included several
niches.  At the same time greater diversity would make the
species more adaptive during periods of high stress.

Obviously, intolerance of or incompatibility with genetic
variation would lead to more rapid speciation and a smaller
range of behaviors within each species.  Small isolated
populations combined with limited variability within each
seems like a recipe for extinction.

