&gt; If you disagree give me an example of a deterministic process which
&gt; contains a random subprocess.
">

Easy.

The following process sorts a handful of stones gathered on a beach
into a linear, left-to-right sequence by size.

Subprocess 1.  Randomly place the stones into a line running left to right.

Subprocess 2.  Randomly choose a pair of adjacent stones.

Subprocess 3.  If the stone (of the pair) on the right is larger, exchange
the positions of these stones.

Return to Subprocess 2, repeating subprocesses 2 and 3 forever.

This process has a deterministic result, placing the stones into decreasing
order of size left-to-right, and keeping them there.  Yet subprocesses
2 and 3 are random subprocesses.

Sometimes processes with random subprocesses generate random
results, and sometimes they generate deterministic ones.  That has
been known for centuries.

Processes with ALL subprocesses deterministic are not guaranteed to
give completely deterministic results either.  If the process exploits
'deterministic chaos' it can 'explode' tiny and inevitable imprecisions in
the specification of initial conditions into full-blown randomness in the
results.
