It is true that random walk with a reflecting barrier obeys different
statistics from an unconstrained random walk.  It is also true that if
you record the maximum excursion of a random value over time that the
maximum must necessarily increase.  Selecting out values of the
maximum complexity necessarily results in the complexity increasing
over time.  But if you start a random walk from the most complex
value, the chances are that it will DEcrease in complexity because
there will ordinarily be far more paths in the direction of decreasing
complexity than in the direction of increasing.  Or, if you will, it
may be a 50-50 chance of increase.  Certainly a random walk is NOT an
inevitable way of producing complexity unless you add enough extra
stipulations (like selecting and preserving extreme cases, exactly the
selection and ratchet I already described) so that the increase in
complexity must be attributed to those additions and not to the
underlying random process.

