The small typo was easy to interpret.  What is a bit more difficult is
this last paragraph about a completely deterministic process not being
deterministic because of 'chaos'.  The fact is that what we call
normally call 'chaos' in the modern sense is really deterministic.  It
is just that it may look random in the same way that a pseudo-random
sequence is deterministic (given a specific seed) but looks random.
The fact that a process may eventually be totally depending on even
tiny differences in starting point or because of rounding errors
produced by calculations done with finite word length floating point
calculations doesn't change the deterministic nature of the outcome It
is just that the result may not be what you expected.
