You shoulda took my course (back when I was teaching!)  Better yet, go
out and get a good intro text book.  For your purpose, buying a
previous edition cheap will do just fine.

For the record, I did highly recommend the Schilthuizen book &quot;Frogs
Flies and Dandelions&quot; about speciation but I also recall that it had
previously been highly recommended to this group, no doubt by Wilkins.

And that book covers Rhagoletis rather fully which allows me to segue
into that topic which is really a separate subthread higher back in
the history of this post.The importance of the example of Rhagoletis,
the Apple Maggot, is to sympatric speciation, one species turning into
two even without any geographic separation.  So having different
species of trees (Hawthorns and Apples in this case) having different
geographic ranges is not the point.  The point is habitat isolation:
each species (or more probably sub-species or race) spends its life on
the preferred type of tree even if the other tree is nearby.  Hence
the two groups are effectively separate from each other even living
completely in the same orchard.  And differences in feeding, whether
food preference or method of harvesting the food, most definitely are
capable of producing habitat or ecological isolation.
